Hi Joseph,

Thans for pointing to your thesis, which I have now read. Good stuff.
It did clear up most of the details I was wondering about, but it
would be handy to have your code available to look at in case there is
something more I&#39;m wondering about.

I am currently working on comparing different ways of encoding
modularity for evolving controllers in the simple game of Cellz, where
agents have radial symmetry. One of the methods will be something very
much like modular neat, but without the speciation and symbiotic
coevolution parts. (If I understand your thesis right, you didn&#39;t find
any evidence that the symbotic coevolution part actually improved
effectiveness.)

I definitely think that the general idea of modular neat is a (the?)
key to scaling up evolutionary computation in certain domains with
inherent symmetry, such as complex visual input. Actually, I&#39;m not
convinced that artificially embryogenetic systems (e g GRN-based)
neccessarily have more to offer in terms of evolvability (though they
might be more interesting from a biological point of view) than the
straightforward approach to modularity taken in neat.

Julian

